# Cursor rules -- NCH Neoplasie (Tumor Histopathology)

## Project

LLM pipeline that assigns ONE final neuro-oncological tumor category per patient
from KISIM pathology report exports. One patient in -> one row out. See
`README.md`, `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`, `docs/DATA_SCHEMA.md`,
`docs/CLINICAL_RULES.md`, `docs/RUNBOOK.md`.

## Hard rules

- NEVER commit real patient data. Tests and fixtures use SYNTHETIC data only.
  `data/raw/`, generated outputs, `.env`, `*.xlsx`/`*.csv`, caches, venvs and
  logs are git-ignored. Run `scripts/check_no_sensitive_files.py` before commits.
- Do NOT invent clinical definitions. The `12_AndereCB` vs `12_Andere`
  distinction is undocumented -- keep both, flag for review, do not guess.
- Missing tumor information is NOT a negative classification. Never drop a
  patient; mark `Keine_Tumorinformation = 1`.
- Exactly ONE `12_*` tumor column may be set to 1 per successfully classified
  patient. Never output multiple categories silently.
- Prefer the current/latest diagnosis; never classify a historical comparison
  diagnosis as the current one.
- Do NOT claim clinical validation. This is decision support.

## Conventions

- Controlled vocabulary + output columns live ONLY in
  `src/tasks/tumor_histopathology/constants.py`. Do not scatter label mappings.
- Environment variables use the `TUMOR_HISTOLOGY_` prefix.
- Production task code lives under `src/tasks/tumor_histopathology/`. Shared,
  task-agnostic roots live in `src/pipeline/paths.py`.
- Keep the architecture simple and linear; do not add unnecessary layers.
- Comments explain intent/constraints, not what the code obviously does.

## Testing

- `python3 -m pytest tests`
- Every new behavior needs a synthetic test. Stub the LLM (`tests/_synthetic.py`);
  never hit the network in tests.
